TRIP COMMENTS: third day of an Attour visit of 2 weeks, with Larry Balch, Thede Tobish, Dan Gibson, Ben King, Guy McCaskie, Terry Moore, Alan Keith, Paul DuMont, Paul Sykes, Jerry Rosenband et al. About 40 birders on island, but the checklist is just what I saw. I spent most of this day with McCaskie, Alan Keith, and Dave Bolen. I have many photos and descriptions, but all rarities were seen by many leaders and hordes of birders. I did not keep track of numbers of common resident birds ("x" on checklist) after the first day. Coverage this day was Casco Cove, mouth of Peaceful River, Navy Town, Massacre Beach, marsh at airport runway, Henderson Valley, and Murder Pt. Weather this date was clear, cold, and very windy

LOCALITY: St. Paul Island--Webster Lake and vicinity
St. Paul Island--Webster Lake and vicinity

TRIP COMMENTS: Field Guides 1987 Alaska tour, Part 1, guided by Bret Whitney & Dave Stejskal.  After a nice breakfast @ 0700, we headed out in 2 vehicles to the breeding cliffs on the n.e. corner of the island.  Packed a lunch and planned to be out most of the day.  Greg took us to a Northern Fur Seal colony with a walkway & blind and gave the group a brief lecture on the seals.  We parked where the dirt road dead ends and headed first south to the top of a ridge and then east to the breeding cliffs.  Spectacular sight!  Walked out to Tolstoi Point and then headed back to cars @ 1600.  After 1800 supper, some of us went out to Staryartiel Point – historic site of 1st settlement on St. George (ca. 250 years old).  The road to this spot goes due west at the first major curve to south past the airport on the man road.  Went on to check Govorushka Lake from road and then to the harbor briefly to chase a Tringa, sp. (probably WOSA) that flushed from marshy area at Govorushka.  Called it quits @ 2300.

Field Guides 1987 Alaska I Part 1 tour, guided by Bret Whitney & Dave Stejskal.  Woke up to west winds and light showers. After breakfast and loading cars, started to drive out of town but were stopped by 2 Tringa sandpipers that flushed from the side of the road.  Watched both trying to fly into the wind when one doubled back and landed in a grassy wet area on west side of town.  After much searching, found that our bird was a WOSA.  Everyone got great looks and then 2nd Wood Sand flew in.  My first taste of vagrant hunting in Alaska.  After excitement died down, we continued on to Bear Lake at the end of the airstrip, checking all likely puddles and wet spots, as well as Upper Lake above town along the way.  When we arrived at Bear Lake, Greg & I went to check smaller pond south of Bear Lake and flushed a male TUDU, which everyone saw fly over.  Checked a few overlooks between the airstrip and Staryartiel looking for TUDU & YBLO.  Drove past Govorushka and up to dump and abandoned vehicles to check for vagrant landbirds.  Continued on to harbor w/o much luck and with a lot of rain.  Checked Staryartiel, Govorushka, and Zapadni Beach & ponds later w/o much luck.  Cumulative list for our day on St. George Island.

Field Guides 1987 Alaska tour, Part 1, guided by Bret Whitney & Dave Stejskal.  Had breakfast at Captain Cook's @ 0630, loaded up taxis, and headed to Peninusla Airways to catch 2 planes to St. George I. in Bering Sea.  Flight scheduled to leave @ 0900.  Birded briefly around Lake Hood outside Peninsula Airways office.  Stopped in King Salmon to refuel (brief stop) and then headed to St. George.  Flew over St. Paul and arrived at St. George ca. lunchtime.  Met at airstrip by Greg McGlashan and drove to St. George Hotel where we checked in and grabbed a quick sandwich.  Put everyone in one 15-pax van (too cramped).  Drove first out to Govorushka Lake on the road that bisects the island (past airstrip) and ends at Zapadni Bay on south side of the island.  Went back to the hotel @ 1830 (dinner scheduled for 1800).  Met Suzie (cook) & Sonny (Suzie's son).  Had our only halibut meal of the stay here (halibut pie).  After supper, most of us went up to Upper Lake above town and a few continued on to Seal Lake east of town (dirt road leads to it), and then walked back through town hoping to spot a vagrant.  Called it quits @ 2230.

TRIP COMMENTS: Historical records from Schwitters, M.T. 2015. Bird species found at Shemya Island, Alaska 1999-2010. U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service Report. AMNWR 2015/01. Homer, Alaska. Entered by Z. Pohlen.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Snowy Owl excerpt from Schwitters (2015): In the Aleutians Snowy Owls are most common in the western islands, where they are probably residents and nest regularly on Attu and casually on Buldir. The species is described as casual in fall and winter in the central Aleutians and casual in winter in the eastern Aleutians. On Attu the birds nest in the uplands, but forage over low elevation habitats and move between the islands of the Near Island group. Gibson and Byrd assess the Snowy Owls that visit Shemya as members of a Near Islands resident population. In the Near Islands the owls' diet is mostly birds (Ancient Murrelets and storm-petrels) (Gibson and Byrd 2007). In the 1970s on Shemya Gibson found Snowy Owls only in his spring visits (Gibson 1981). The USFWS winter visits to Shemya found Snowy Owls in two winters (1993 and 1995) (Byrd and Scharf 2003). During our visits to Shemya 1999-2010 Snowy Owls were found sporadically in the springs of the period 1999-2002 (1999, 2001 and 2002); none were found in the other seasonal visits in that period. In those spring visits usually only one individual was found, but perhaps seven birds were recorded in the spring of 2002. However, beginning with the short visit in late spring of 2004 through 2010, Snowy Owls were found every spring and every fall. During the spring visits the owls were more numerous than in the fall visits. The spring of 2005 and 2006 found up to five individuals, spring of 2007 found perhaps 14 owls visiting the island (though some were likely returns of some individuals), perhaps as many as eight (repeats likely) where found in the spring of 2008 and the spring of 2010 found as many as ten. The fall surveys in 2005 and 2006 found just one individual, fall of 2007 recorded three separate individuals. Fall 2010 had one that was present nearly the entire season. This apparent increase in owls corresponded with the removal of foxes from Attu. Snowy Owls were found in all plumages from totally white males to heavily spotted juveniles. The varying plumages did assist in identifying individuals. The owls did present a challenge in determining age and sex. Note. A highly informative paper describing the aging and sexing Snowy owls is available (Josephson 1980). Some information on the owls' diet while on Shemya was observed. A female was seen consuming a male Green-winged Teal (9 May 2006). During that observation the owl ejected a pellet that was retrieved. The pellet was the total indigestible remains of a Roof Rat. A second old pellet was recovered that same spring and the contents examined; the skulls of two rodents (at least one Roof Rat) were found. Finally, security personnel shared an anecdote of a Snowy Owl catching, killing and eating (in the beam of their vehicle's lights) an Arctic Fox at night in March of 2006.

TRIP COMMENTS: Our group bought the five-day plan, and when it ended we didn't want to leave. Seeing and photographing the cliff-nesting colonies of seabirds was one of the greatest experiences of my life, and we suffered only a single, brief rainstorm. We were there June 13-17, but I kept a running list rather than daily lists (there would have been much duplication if I had), and so chose the middle date to make this single entry. The seabirds were essentially uncountable, and I was there for the experience more than for making counts, which the guides would be doing anyway. We had two guides, Rick Knight from Tennessee and Dylan Radin from the U. of Ariz., who were both terrific.  No effort data.
SPECIES COMMENTS: the guides were pleasantly surprised to see this apparent adult on the east side of the island

VENT Attu Cruise - Day 12 (Attu Island)

Today was our last full day covering the greater Coast Guard station area and our three groups divided up to cover the three major sections. The morning was rather wet, and there were periods of wind and rain that almost recalled the weather that had been predicted for Attu. To be sure, our group was incredibly lucky for the wonderful weather conditions during our time there. The Spotted Redshank was again in position at Smew Pond, and it seemed to have gotten used to our presence and allowed closer approach | a welcome change from its first day when it would flush at almost any distance. There clearly was an arrival of Sharp-tailed Sandpipers overnight, possibly migrant birds that were grounded by the inclement weather. The Smew Pond group had four Sharp-taileds, including at least a couple that literally "dropped from the sky" in front of them. Along Debris Beach we found three Sharp-taileds together at about 9:00 and found the birds to be incredibly approachable. After prolonged scope views at 100 feet we closed the distance to about 20 feet while the birds unconcernedly foraged on the upper part of the beach. As we moved down the beach a fourth Sharp-tailed appeared and joined the other three, and later in the day their number had swollen to seven. Photographers had a field day with these birds, which remained just as confiding throughout the day. Two groups had single Pectoral Sandpipers, and some people got to study both species in the same day, comparing the brighter plumage, mostly unstreaked breasts, and streaked undertails coverts of the Sharpies.  OTHER FAUNA: MAMMALS: Minke Whale; Harbor Seal; Sea Otter.

Today got off to an early good start as well. Before most groups had even loaded Larry Balch called from Navy Town asking, "Does anyone want to see a Snowy Owl?" The Spotted Redshank was feeding in its "usual" spot and seemed to have become accustomed to groups of tourists gawking at it. We watched it spend about five minutes trying to swallow an oversized minnow that seemed to be stuck in its gullet. We were worried we might have to administer emergency care, but eventually the fish was swallowed and we can report that our redshank did live to see another day. Another massive rarity chase was set in motion when we glanced through the mist and fog to the back side of Smew Pond where a mid-sized shorebird was foraging. It turned out to be a juvenile Sharp-tailed Sandpiper, an Asian species that we had expected to see before this and which we began to worry that we would miss. Sharp-taileds are uncommon migrants throughout western Alaska, and can even be found predictably in the Pacific Northwest states during September and October, but which is accidental elsewhere in the country. It was a welcome lifer for much of the ship and so groups started converging on Smew Pond. Almost everyone got the bird immediately, but when one of the last groups arrived we had a bit of a scare. The Sharp-tailed flew upriver and was lost from sight for about 20 minutes. We tried to carefully walk the riverbed to flush the bird again and others of us carefully scanned the pond edge in case it had returned to its favored spots. Even when we knew where it was the Sharp-tailed had been very difficult to spot, and continuously moved in and out of the grasses at the edge. Perhaps it was not surprising then that the bird was missed. I had been the appointed riverwalker, and when I reached the pond I decided to try playing its call since it had earlier shown some level of tape response. As soon as I keyed up the iPod a shorebird started flying directly for me from the far side of the pond. It turned out to be the Sharp-tailed and on its return visit it gave great looks to the worried recent arrivals and lifted a great burden from the leaders' shoulders. We spent a long time absorbing its key field marks, which sunk in especially well for those of us that had carefully studied similar Pectoral Sandpipers in previous days. Several groups undertook ambitious afternoon walks. My group headed up Henderson Valley to Bird Canyon and Lake Elwood. Lake Elwood produced another new bird for the trip: an American Wigeon. This was perhaps the only time that I had seen Eurasian Wigeon (2) outnumber American (1), and it was one of the better comparative studies I have had. The gray head of the American contrasted markedly with its breast (little to no contrast on Eurasian). Almost on command, the American rose out of the water and flapped, revealing its diagnostic white underwing. Our other neat find on that long walk was a second Snowy Owl, this one a pure white adult sitting high on the rocky cliffs of Terrible Mountain. OTHER FAUNA: MAMMALS: Minke Whale; Harbor Seal; Sea Otter.

Wind switched from moderate S-ish to 25-35 NW; 40s with some drizzly/ dense fog early, mostly clearing to partly cloudy later with occasional screens of mist moving through; We dropped folks off at the airport (Brad Benter, Barbara Carlson, etc) and they left on a morning plane after two days of cancelled flights - arriving were folks traveling with Aaron Lang and Dave Porter (WBA group). Sites visited thereafter: WBL, lunch, Pumphouse Lake (Jack Snipe/ Common Snipe), Quarry Upper Cut (no sign of Pallas's Rosefinch today), Quarry Crab Pots, SW Point, Tonki Marsh (flushed a NEW Jack Snipe), Main Crab Pots, Hutch Hill (chasing Olive-backed Pipit found earlier in the day by SS).

Birds seen while conducting wildlife surveys for the USFWS.----Arrived on island about 1:30 in the G4. Given what had shown up on St. Paul recently, I expected some lingering landbirds from the past storm. As I was riding the bus to the 600 building, we flushed a flock of 15 Brambling of the road and had a feeling it was going to be interesting. I imagine everything seen today is the leftovers from the previous storm. Calm overcast conditions. Unusual pleasant conditions. Exceptionally low tide. Island seems dry with few fluddles.

Birds seen while conducting wildlife surveys for the USFWS.----Heavy fog in the morning, limiting visibility to 200m but quickly burning off. Light southwest winds all day calming to still air in the evening. The seas were one of the calmest I have ever seen them here. Fog started to roll back in around 20:00.  Ran low on fuel and couldn't fill up because of the holiday. Ended up walking to my survey points on the western half of the island, which was nice and birdy. The obvious highlight was the Kentish Plover.

George day 2: Low overcast, low 40s, fog at Ulakaia. Winds 10kt North--A day of resights. Started the morning by going to the Ulakaia Auklet colony and spending 3 hours surrounded by thousands of Least Auklets as they socialized. An incredible experience, and a first for Matt and I both. We were able to record 40! different Auklets during that time, a substantial increase from last season’s pace, although when they were here no banding had been done in 3 years. Afterwards, we ate lunch (Shin ramen and a burrito for me) and then walked the beaches below Village west and Rosy Finch Kittiwake plots, resighting around 45! Black and Red-legged Kittiwakes. A very productive day for survival data. --After a dinner of Amy’s dog food chili, I set out for Garden Cove. Upper Lake was stocked as always, and I also checked Seal Lake for my first time—9/10 chill space but 4/10 vagrant trap. A true tundra lake, it’s banks fall directly to standing water with no mudflat or reedy stretch. Reminded me of all the knee-deep North Slope lakes I’ve waded through. It did have both Mergansers, but aside from ducks I doubt too much shows up here. -Garden Cove had a few things (as I expect it always will), but I didn’t consider the North wind hitting the island which funneled right down the cove and mostly ruined its use as a windbreak for vagrant passerines. The birds I did find were near the creek mouth where the canyon bends. --One Steller’s Sea Lion (my FOS) on Garden Cove beach, and a couple of Fur Seals at Staraya in the afternoon. Several ARFOs seen, including at least one all-white animal.

TRIP COMMENTS: Birds seen while conducting wildlife surveys for the USFWS.----Overcast in morning becoming partly sunny in afternoon, 10-15 mph W/SW winds all day. New influx of birds today with numerous Gray-streaked Flycatchers being the highlight. The day started off slow, and I finished most of my eastern interior surveys (with only a few Brambling, Eastern Yellow Wagtail, and flyover RNPH to note) before swinging by the Grand Canyon around 11. The NW corner of the Grand Canyon had 2 Rustic Bunting, 2 Pine Grosbeak, 1 Olive-backed Pipit, 1 Eyebrowed Thrush, and 1 Gray-streaked Flycatcher amongst a dozen Brambling. Things picked up quickly with consistent EYTH, GSFL, and RUBU throughout the perimeter road and western part of the island. Redeployed 1 SOSP ARU in a territory on South Beach.

St. G day 19: Ledgenester productivity intro --With a plan to work at High Bluffs all afternoon, I used the morning to hike to Garden Cove. I believe this is the first time I’ve birded there without seeing any Bramblings, but the Eagle and some bank swallows were around. The cove is earning its name too—the hillsides were a lush green and under partly blue skies (the south side is always nicer), I found many new FOS flowering plants that I’ll have to work on identifying. --Came home for a quick lunch of leftover chili and cornbread, and somehow chipped one of my back molars on some crusty cornbread I guess? Super bizarre—don’t think I even realized it was that easy to chip a real chunk off a molar like that. Hope it’s not serious. Also bit my inner lip really hard and drew blood. --Afterwards, I hustled up to High Bluffs, where I met Ricky and did my first productivity checks of my plots there. I was originally gonna do Red Bluffs, but Heather thinks that one person likely won’t be able to do High Bluffs alone (as Ricky was planning to), so I’m splitting it with him now. Fun to be up there in a fog that ebbed and flowed with little wind to chill me. -Once we got back, I used the opportunity to check Govorushka and Turtle Lakes before heading to bed. Home by 11, where I then bit the same spot on my lip 3 more times while trying to eat pasta.

TRIP COMMENTS: St. George day 46: High Bluffs in the fog --Left the house a little before noon and hiked with Ricky up to High Bluffs, where we sat in the fog until 1800. --Then came home, ate dinner, and after hearing about a potential WHAU sighting at Pop Plot 22 on Red Bluffs, I hiked out to give it a look. TRIP COMMENTS: St. George day 49: Solo day off--With the others off working, I spent midday reading “Two in the Far North” by Margaret Murie and eating junk food. At 1700h, I decided enough was enough and took a fungal and botanical walk through garden cove. The vegetation there is truly spectacular—twisted stalk lines the upper creek like subjects in the court of a king, and fields of buttercup and lupine paint the hills with yellow and purple as you get closer to the sea. The creek itself is an elfin dream, with perfect lush moss covering every rock and saxifrages still blooming in the shade. Hanging gardens of cinquefoil line the small cliff above, and the seaside slope towards cascade point is now a waist-deep forest of blooming puutchkie and lupin flowers, which create an alternating pattern of chartreuse and lilac. -Once at the beach, I swam (or rather dunked) into the waves which were surprisingly fierce today for GC. Then I laid out nude like one of the ~75 harbor seals further down the beach and enjoyed the warm black sand and thick humid air. Eventually I dressed and returned home for Matt’s birthday party! Lauren baked an amazing mustard-glazed salmon fillet with roasted delicata squash and balsamic-caramelized onions, as well as baked potatoes and a cast-iron berry crisp. We sat and chatted for awhile, and then went to bed as another day of pop counts began to loom.

Large owl with black barring over white, white face and yellow eyes. July like Harry Potter's pet :-). This is rare sighting for Anchorage. The bird was perched over a house roof. See photo.

Here is my listing of one of the coolest lifers ever.  Thanks to Aaron, I followed through immediately after he posted while observing the bird.  After a circuitous drive I finally saw several birds sporting their huge lenses.  Sure enough, perched on the roof of the house with the Address of 2306 Susitna drive right in the vicinity of Lynn Ary Park, was this large beautiful white owl with gray marking.  I parked my car and turned it off and watched for many minutes.  It turned out I did not have to rush because this individual appeared very relaxed and settled for a while.  Though it stayed alert watching it's surroundings and as a result I was able to have long looks of those piercing, pretty yellow eyes it is known for as it rotated it's head many times.  No binoculars needed but I used them anyway to get close-ups of those pupils.  It is true what they say about it's large size as I immediately said to myself "wow, what a big bird"!

SPECIES COMMENTS: A party of six skiing from Glen Alps to Indian spotted a large white owl on the snow along Ship Creek. The habitat is a snow covered subalpine valley with sparse hemlock. The large owl was bright white with dark barring on body and an all white face. The owl sat on the snow looking at us for 5-8 minutes and then took flight and flew out of sight. Only terrible iPhone pictures were taken.

*casual for Anchorage; there are only 2 records on eBird, but roughly 6-8 records in total for the Municipality. Only light to moderate barring would indicate either an immature male/adult female.----Observed distantly on driftwood near the water's edge approximately halfway between the Campbell Creek mouth and Carr-Gottstein Park. As the tide rose it relocated to a washed up dead spruce snag a little ways away from the rising water. Seen by many Anchorage birders tonight with a very small window of daylight remaining after I got word out. Technology for the win!

TRIP COMMENTS: Participated in a joint Anc. Audubon/Mat-Su Birders charter to Middleton Is., arranged by Scott Christy. A second charter group birded on May 8, 2005. We flew to Middleton Is. on a TransNorthern Airways modified DC-3, the same aircraft that was used in the 2011 movie "The Big Year." Basically birded the NE half of Middleton Island. Walking was made somewhat difficult due to the deep sand in most of the walking areas on the upper levels of the island. Birded with fellow Mat-Su Birders'' member, Nancy Moore. A Smith's Longspur was seen by some of the birders, but Nancy and I were unable to find it.
SPECIES COMMENTS: This bird was at the NE tip of the island and was a real surprise, and was one of the first birds that we saw.  Several birders tried to get close enough for good photos, but the owl kept moving.  An ADN reporter took part in the May 8, 2005 charter, and in his ADN article ("Bird Trap in the Gulf," May 15, 2005), referred to this bird as the "newly resident" snowy owl.
Observed by many Anchorage Audubon trip

TRIP COMMENTS: We started birding around the old Airforce buildings, then dropped down to the base of the westside bluffs and worked the willows south to the bowl area. We then walked out to the beach at the old shipwreck and worked the beach south all the way to the south point of the island. We worked back north along the bluffs back to the big bowl area, then back to the top of the island and back to the Airforce buildings. Weather was partly cloudy in the morning, wind SW <5; light rain in the afternoon and wind E to 10; turned to rain in evening. Steve Heinl, Rich MacIntosh, Thede Tobish, and Gary Rosenberg.

We birded the entire west bluff from the north end south to the bowl area. Fairly slow for passerines, as has been the case since we arrived on 21 September. Also, the north point. Weather was partly cloudy, wind SSE 5, warm. Steve Heinl, Rich MacIntosh, Thede Tobish, and Gary Rosenberg.

We did not start birding until late morning due high winds. We birded the north point for several hours and had great, close views of Black-footed Albatross and Fork-tailed and Leach's storm-petrels and others. Rich and I birded east along the north shore to the lagoon at the NE corner (high tide, so not many shorebirds) and back; Tobish birded the beach SE of the FAA station as well.  Weather in the morning, wind SW 30+ and clear; changed to S 15 later in the day. Steve Heinl, Rich MacIntosh, Thede Tobish, and Gary Rosenberg.

Arrived on the island at 0930 via Alaska Air Transit. We started birding at 11:00 at the big bowl at the south end of the westside bluffs and worked our way north along the bluff then up onto the runway; we then walked out to the north point to do a seawatch for an hour. Weather was partly cloudy, 60 degrees, wind SW 5-10; Steve Heinl, Rich MacIntosh, Thede Tobish, and Gary Rosenberg.

We started birding the westside bluffs below the Airforce buildings and worked north until the habitat ran out; walked to the north point then east across the deflation plain to the east point and south across the lagoon and shore along the east side and back to the Airforce buildings. Weather was partly cloudy in the morning, wind S 5-10; then clouded up, light rain by noon and steady rain by evening with wind SE to 30 all night. Steve Heinl, Rich MacIntosh, Thede Tobish, and Gary Rosenberg.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Have pictures. This bird is not rare here. I saw them several years in a row.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Just after dusk, glided across hwy 10-15 feet above roadbed, about 100 feet in from of vehicle, view of individual traveling away, no view of head, mostly the back and tail view, medium sized raptor, light coloration, mottled appearance like a juvenile owl.

Flew very near us at tree top level.  Flew over the top of the tree and down onto the tundra where it seemed to disappear.  It did not continue to fly low over the tundra as a harrier would. It did not have the same shape wings as a harrier.  It had a very squashed face and was entirely white.  We have seen several harriers while birding between Homer and Fairbanks and this bird was larger.
My uncle reported seeing a large white owl on a light pole near Seekins and after I raced over there, found that it was indeed a Snowy Owl!

I drove out to the Long Island causeway in hopes that I could see it from there with a spotting scope. Though it had flown to a different spot by the time I got there, it was still visible from the road. I got a poor photo through my scope which I will attach later. It had a good amount of barring on it, so not an adult male. County 1st for me!

TRIP COMMENTS: Target sp. - Snowy Owl.  Seen by many yesterday.  Very Stormy.  Temp. 37 degrees F.  Rain heavy.--Winds from the east steady at 20 to 30 plus mph.  Gusts easily 40 plus mph.  Outing duration: 2 hrs. 10 min.  Distance: 3.6 miles.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Because of the storm decided to leave my camera in the car.  A group heading in as I was heading out said they had not seen the owl after looking for some time.  Briefly looked in the area where it was seen  yesterday with no luck.  Decided to walk out to the channel islands hoping it had taken some shelter from the weather there.  Found it in the large furthest east island that is almost directly out from the end of the trail (past the bench).  On the leeward side of the island facing the grass flats it flushed out of a tree nearly directly overhead, very low and close. Got a good look of a white owl with dark barring.  Glassed it as it circled the flats a couple times and then flew to the next island west.  Got another good look walking towards that island when it rose circled the island a couple times then appeared to land again. I circled the island a couple of times searching for it but did not see it again.

SPECIES COMMENTS: On the Kodiak Christmas Bird Count. This Snowy Owl was the first ever found on a Kodiak archipelago Christmas Bird Count.  The bird had been present in or near the city of Kodiak since 29 October 2001. It was usually seen at night near the launching ramp at the Dog Bay boat harbor, where it was hunting rats under the street lights. I scattered corn near the launching ramp to attract more rats in the week before the count.  Ian Bruce and I found the bird at ten minutes after midnight on the morning of the count.

I was standing at the window of my Grandview Hotel room looking across a lighted area behind the hotel when a snowy owl landed in the top of a birch tree there, probably about 30 feet away. Large owl with rounded head, solid white except for some small blackish spots on wings and back; yellow eyes.  I am familiar with this species having lived in Alaska for 20 years, with almost yearly trips to Prudhoe Bay in the summer where they are not uncommon breeders.
I got a very good look at it in the car headlights- a straight on view then it flew. White face with cap distinctive, as well as bars on side. Looked like first year female illustrated in Sibley's.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Seen from the second pullout at the top of the pass, about 1/2 mile SE.  Viewed with scope in brilliant sunlight. Plumage on the back and head appeared to be pure white.  Known by locals to be in that area.

TRIP COMMENTS: Marcus Roening & Heather Ballash, 50-55F, 10-15 mph north winds, blue skies with high clouds.  Rented an ATV for a half day dorm Dwayne & Samantha for $80.  Drove around the south end of the lake, up to the pass, a quick stop at the quiet bird cliffs and then one final grand circle along the beach around the whole village in the shining sun.

Today the winds went calm after a week of high North winds.
This produced a Brambling and a dozen new Lapland Longspurs, as well as the best bird, an Orange-flanked Blue-tail at 5 p.m. This bird was present for only an hour, then never seen again.
Today was also the day of the best late Northward push of alcids, including our highest number of Ancient Murrelets.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Conservatively 5. Two seen at once serval different times. All immature.
Found by Chris Feeney on the beach south of Troutman Lake.
An immature bird flushed from ~60m north of the road and flew a ways before sitting down again. Horrible photos. Seen just past MP 7.

All birds seen from the air flying low level in this area. All seen within 5 miles. Mostly adults, with at least one that showed some barring (not a fledgling). Either they’re breeding here, or happen to all be together during a post breeding dispersal.

TRIP COMMENTS: Data collected for a study investigating bird use of wetland habitats in the National Petroleum Reserve-Alaska. This study was conducted at two interior (Singiluk and Square Lake) and three outer Arctic Coastal Plain sites (Meade River Delta, Island Lake, and East Long Lake) in the National Petroleum Reserve in Alaska (NPRA) in 1977 and 1978. Comparative data were collected in the same years from a Beaufort Sea costal site near Prudhoe Bay (Storkersen Point). Additional information can be found in "Use of Habitats by Birds in the National Petroleum Reserve - Alaska" 1981 by Derksen, D.V., T.C. Rothe, and W.D. Eldridge.Observations made by Mike North; Data transcribed by Nicole Hudson; Data uploaded to eBird by Z. Pohlen; This and additional USGS Alaska Science Center bird checklists are available in a U.S. Geological Survey data release, https://doi.org/10.5066/P950QX28. DOI 10.5066/P950QX28.

Comparative data were collected in the same years from a Beaufort Sea costal site near Prudhoe Bay (Storkersen Point). Additional information can be found in "Use of Habitats by Birds in the National Petroleum Reserve - Alaska" 1981 by Derksen, D.V., T.C. Rothe, and W.D. Eldridge.Observations made by Mike North; Data transcribed by Nicole Hudson; Data uploaded to eBird by Z. Pohlen; This and additional USGS Alaska Science Center bird checklists are available in a U.S. Geological Survey data release, https://doi.org/10.5066/P950QX28. DOI 10.5066/P950QX28.

TRIP COMMENTS: Field Guides' 1993 Alaska tour guided by Dave Stejskal & Chris Benesh.  Left hotel @ 0620 in courtesy vans and checked into Alaska Airlines flight to Utqiagvik.  Some folks stopped for a quick bite for breakfast in airport.  Flight was late leaving Anchorage, and we arrived in Utqiagvik ca. lunchtime.  Met by Toby, our driver, at the airport.  She took us to Top of the World Hotel where we unloaded our bags.  Rooms weren't ready for us yet, so we went over to Pepe's North of the Border next door to eat lunch.  Checked into rooms after lunch (no room for me & Chris) and then went out to the Hunt Camp and the base of the point, making a few stops along the way.  Fog rolled in @ 1600 and made birding essentially impossible.  We made a stop at the museum/hotel at N.A.R.L. to kill some time, but fog persisted.  Had dinner at Pepe's @ 1900 and decided not to bird after dinner because of the fog.  Chris and I got a room at the Arctic Hotel.

Field Guides' 1993 Alaska tour guided by Dave Stejskal & Chris Benesh.  Had breakfast at Pepe's @ 0600 and drove out to Freshwater Lake and then to the start of Cakeeater Rd.  Left here @ 1000 and drove back to Top of the World to check out and send bags off to airport.  Arrived at airport @ 1030 and got boarding passes from Alaska Airlines (I had left tickets with them the day that we arrived).  Gave a $50 tip to Toby.  Flight left @ 1130 (no fog delay) and arrived in Anchorage @ 1500.  Had lunch on flight.  Made dinner reservation at Regal Alaskan Inn for 1830.  Did final checklist after dinner at our hotel.

Field Guides' 1993 Alaska tour guided by Dave Stejskal & Chris Benesh.  Had breakfast at Pepe's @ 0730 (normally don't open until 0900 on Sundays) and then drove out to Hunt Camp again.  Walked out part of the way (ca. 1 mile) and then back to Pepe's for lunch @ 1300.  Drove out to Freshwater lake after lunch, birding here until dinner time when fog came back in.  After dinner, drove back out to Hunt Camp and also checked out the start of the Cakeeater Rd. to where it was washed out (ca. 1 mile in).  Back to hotel @ 2300.  Water was ope ca. 1/4-1/3 mile off shore today, but winds from north kept ice in.
General area around Prudhoe Bay and Deadhorse. We were able to secure permission/access to get to the edge of the bay.

TRIP COMMENTS: An astonishing concentration of Arctic Terns and Sabine's Gulls feeding on euphausiids. Estimated as many as 50,000 Arctic Terns. George Divoky called from Cooper Island where he was seeing 2,000 terns; and in Barrow there were thousands along the beach, thousands over the bay, and a ribbon of many thousands along the horizon to Plover Point. Sabine's Gulls were also in huge numbers, not as many as the terns, but certainly 2000-5000 Sabine's Gulls.

Bird watching Team 2007: --Holger Schielzeth, Wolfgang Forstmeier, Mihai Valcu & myself----Bird data:--We worked, the hole day, for different “Sandpiper Project’s” from the Max Planck Institute for Ornithology. Us main study site was around 9 km2 next to the BASK Building in Barrow.--Also we used a lot of time to go for Birds, do Seewatching and we checked almost every places we could retch by car or ATV´s. It was our final mornings birding in Barrow and indeed in Alaska as this was the final day of the trip. We decided to head out to the point to get some final views of Polar Bear. As we drove along the coast road the male Snowy Owl from yesterday was perched close to the road on the edge of town, this is a stunning looking bird, almost pure white, and we had much better views today. Otherwise we saw the usual range of birds including Semipalmated Plover, Arctic Redpoll, large numbers of Spectacled Eider (35) and King Eider (1000's), White-billed Diver (6) and Pacific Diver (4). We recorded two flocks of Pomarine Skua (12 and 8) heading north-east, these appeared to be migrating birds. It was soon time to head back to our hotel and pack for our flight back to Anchorage via Fairbanks at 11:30 landing in Anchorage at 14:45.

TRIP COMMENTS:
Originally entered in My Birding from HBW Alive (birdlist ID: 1402271). Prepared and uploaded by eBird staff; taxonomy updated and locations reconciled.

Original My Birding birdlist title: Gaswell Road, Barrow, North Slope Borough, Alaska (12 Jun 2016 05:00). Original territory and coordinates: USA (United States) (71.2564, -156.5514).

Birdlist Comments:
Field Guides w Dave Stejskal & Tom Johnson

We were up at 07:30 for a 08:00 breakfast and then spent the morning (09:00-14:30) at Barrow Point slowly working our way along the headland scanning and checking for birds. There were numerous Glaucous Gull on the frozen Chukchi sea and on the clear areas of water were several thousand King Eider, 30+ Spectacled Eider, 15 Pacific Diver, 6 White-billed Diver while overhead passed the occasional flock of Snow Goose. Around the old whaling station were Snow Bunting and Arctic Redpoll of the race exilipes. Martin, scanning the pack ice with his scope, exclaimed ‘Polar Bear! And there amongst the shards of ice were two Polar Bear, even at this distance they were impressive animals and we watched as one tossed around a large block of whale blubber. The next three hours were spent watching these animals as they swam along the ice edge, played with a traffic cone used to mark local hunters way across the ice and did a great deal of sleeping. ----We headed back to the hotel for coffee and a siesta and then out to the North Lights Restaurant for another Korean meal, our food intake now down to breakfast, a few snacks and then dinner before another eight hours or so in the field. We started the afternoon by birding the Freshwater Lake Road which runs south-west from the airport. We stopped at the end of the road and spread out, the theme had become to spend time birding and taking photographs alone but within site of the group. I headed over to the freshwater lake with Ian as we had both spotted a pair of Pacific Diver that we both wanted to photograph. The lake was large and deep and as well as the divers supported six Spectacled Eider and two Red-throated Diver, the margins inhabited by Arctic Tern, Long-billed Dowitcher, Pectoral Sandpiper, Red-necked Phalarope and Grey Phalarope. It was fantastic birding and our ‘allocated’ two hours at the site flew by in no time at all. ----After spending the morning on Freshwater Lake Road we headed to Cakeeater Road and Gas Pipe Road birding it until 01:30. On the pool along Cakeeater Road was a nice selection of waders including Baird's Sandpiper, White-rumped Sandpiper and by now the usual and familiar Western Sandpiper, Semipalmated Sandpiper and Pectoral Sandpiper. Onto Gas Pipe Road and out onto the tundra I spent my time with four species, firstly, Spectacled Eider, Steller’s Eider and Red-throated Diver on their tundra breeding pools enjoying great views. But my highlight was undoubtedly spending time with pair of Pomarine Skua at the nest.  It was a real privilege to see them on their breeding grounds in all their splendour with spoons and menacing appearance – uber cool and to be dive bombed by them so that they were no more than 3m away was for me perhaps the highlight of my time in Alaska. Today had been a fantastic days birding with some real star birds.

The morning started rather foggy and dreary, a big change from the amazingly warm weather we had been experiencing (up to 21c yesterday) and much more akin to the weather we were expecting. However, fairly quickly the fog cleared and the morning was gloriously sunny although rain set-in in the afternoon. We spent the morning on the Gas Pipeline Road and Cakeater Road, one of the first birds was a stunning almost all white male Snowy Owl. A 1st winter Thayer's Gull flew overhead and we enjoyed the waders around the lagoon here including some stunning Western Sandpiper.

LOCALITY: Utqiaġvik (town; please use a more specific location)
TRIP COMMENTS: Birding from 20:30 - 1:00, after dinner. With Ben, John, and Sam. Started by looking for the GRYE Ben had seen earlier in the day, (on a mudflat right in town) with no luck. A quick cemetery check produced 1 SAVS and a couple LALO. -Then on to the Baleen Palm feeders and Gravel Pit tanks, both of which we sea-watched from. ~80 GLGU presumably over a hidden whale carcass and a few Jaeger sp. seen here. -Next we checked Nunavak road and others adjacent to it, where we found RUBL, VATH, AMPI, and SEOW. -After that we drove to the base of Pt. Barrow where we enjoyed the midnight sun over the Chutchki sea ice. -Finally we checked the northeast outskirts of town and trash lagoon, where we found WIPT, SNOW, and AMPI.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Nearly pure white bird on the NE outskirt of town. Flew past the car and landed on a telephone pole before flying off.

Utqiaġvik (town; please use a more specific location)
TRIP COMMENTS: Birding from 22:50-1:30 with Sam and Tara. Winds SW at 18kt per Windy app. Skies overcast and occasionally snowing. Snowmelt continues to occur rapidly, with birding spots usually looking quite different from one day to the next (this accentuates our unfamiliarity with the town). --Started by going south to Nunavak road, bypassing the seawatch spot (we looked earlier today, Eiders were still moving in smaller numbers). The AMPI and VATH continue, but a surprise was our FOS BASA, in an awesome little line with WESA and SESA in front of it. WESA continue in higher numbers than SESA. --Afterwards we checked the Baleen Palm feeders (dead) and the Cemetery, which finally produced JB’s lifer Common and Hoary Redpolls, sitting next to each other on one of the crosses. Several Snow Buntings also frolicked in bouquets of synthetic florets. --At this point we dropped Tara back off, and continued north to Cake Eater rd. An immaculate Snowy Owl started us off nicely. Lots of Geese and a smattering of peeps continue, as well as the continuing pair of American GWTE and the PESA found yesterday. New, however, were 8 NOPI—spread all along the road but mostly in pairs. Several TUSW also gave great views. --Other: Learned today that “Nuna” means Tundra in Inupiat; explains Nunavak rd. Also noticed on Google Maps that Cake eater rd. becomes Eastfield rd. before hitting Gas Well (?) Does anyone call it that? -Also of note: we saw none of these but others from the field team saw DUNL, YBLO, and Myrtle Warbler along Cake eater earlier today. All FOS for us.

Our last morning in Utqiagvik was spent birding along the Freshwater Lake Road.  The road was partially flooded and a muddy mess past the cemetery, so we parked by the cemetery and walked/birded on foot along the road to the end and back.  I'm guessing the section that we walked was about 1 mile, and the 3-mile estimate on Distance includes observations of birds seen from the bus as we drove from town to the cemetery.

Brian Gibbons and I did a little late evening scouting out the Nunavak Road after dinner.  We were primarily interested in checking a couple of places where Buff-breasted Sandpipers established leks a few hundred meters off the road in 2019, but we could not locate any Buff-breasted Sandpipers.  Accordingly, most of our 3 hours was spent tromping across the tundra on either side of the Nunavak Road.

TRIP COMMENTS: Our final morning sea-watching from the runway beach, with many other birders present! The kittiwake numbers dropped off dramatically, Ross's Gulls were moving in various directions, and there was a nice push of Common Eiders. The Polar Bear mother and 2 cubs continue, but there was a new (subadult?) bear in their usual spot, so the family group was wandering around a lot more which was fun to watch. There was a Spotted Seal hauled up on the icy lagoon, and a juvenile Walrus moved W through the surf! Multiple Arctic Foxes in view from the runway.--9-16+mph variably W to NW wind, mostly cloudy, 27F (18F wind chill), low tide at 9:34am and then rising.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Moderately-marked type flushed into view along the runway by an Arctic Fox. Eventually flew off down the point.

TRIP COMMENTS: Checklist of all birds seen from the Barrow road system between 11 AM and 6:30 PM. White-out blizzard conditions (and getting the van stuck) delayed our birding until around 11 AM when the weather cleared and visibility improved.
By ATV with local guide Herman. Many Ross’s Gulls south west of the point. Calm conditions

This was our first of 3 extended sea watches on the day, all conducted from a spot opposite the old naval airstrip, just south of the base of the Point.  Visibility was good, with partly to mostly cloudy skies, but high ceiling, and winds were light until just before we quit to go back to town for a pit stop, and to pick up the other members of our group, who were at the Heritage Center.  We experienced a nice movement of Ross's Gulls, including some groups flying high overhead, coming from behind us and heading SW.  Kittiwake numbers were a pale shadow of yesterday, but still impressive.  The Polar Bear family (mother and 2 cubs) were still hanging out in the vicinity, and, there was another lone adult bear a few hundred meters away.  We also had an Arctic Fox (hanging near the bear family), as well as a Walrus (in the surf right off the beach), the latter representing only the 2nd time I can recall having seen the species in Barrow.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Moderately marked bird that I would guess to be an adult female.  It looked very similar to the individual that we saw yesterday near the beginning of Cake Eater Road.

TRIP COMMENTS: Observer(s): Red Seeberger. Citizen science observations from across the Northwest Arctic Borough reported between 1998-2021 as part of an annual community bird sighting contest. The contest is run by the National Park Service in Kotzebue with collaboration from the Selawik National Wildlife Refuge. The contest began as a community outreach event to encourage appreciation of the phenomenon of migratory birds returning to the Arctic. Residents from across the region call in their observations by telephone. The contest typically runs from April 1 - May 31 each year and engages local knowledge and observers spread widely across the landscape. Historical observations compiled and uploaded by Z. Pohlen.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Large, pure white owl flying along ridge line above Mt. Prindle campground.

Seen only briefly. Seen landing on a ridge above us, perhaps 200 yards away and backlit. Got about 30 seconds looking at it,  all white plumage and the right size for a snowy owl. When it flew away it flew like an owl. Not heard and didn't get a picture but feel very good about it being a snowy owl.
